osic detritus (22-24{\%}), phytoplankton (71-79{\%}) and benthic diatoms (89-93{\%}) were up to twofold greater than those in winter and spring (13{\%}, 40-59{\%} and 45-81{\%}, respectively). We conclude that the digestive physiology (e.g., digestive enzyme production) of mussels responds to shifts in dietary components during the year. {\textcopyright} 2001 Elsevier Science B.V.},
